Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read the Prime Minister’s address for the latest information.

The Turks and Caicos Islands has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For further information see, Return to the UK.
Entry and borders
The Turks and Caicos Islands’ borders will remain closed until 01 June 2020.
All regional and international commercial passenger and private flights, along with international seafaring, will cease to operate into the Turks and Caicos Islands. Cargo and courier flights, and emergency flights e.g. medical evacuations, will continue. Cargo vessels will continue to operate into the Turks and Caicos Islands. Anyone arriving on emergency flights, for example to provide support in TCI, are subject to obligatory quarantine for 14 days. More information is available on the TCI Government website.
Those who wish to leave the Turks and Caicos Islands will be allowed to do so during this period, but will not be allowed to re-enter while borders remain closed.
Further information on risks to travellers, avoidance measures, symptoms and how to self-quarantine is available at TCI Ministry of Health.
Local measures
A Night curfew, from 8pm until 5am, is in effect from 04 May 2020 until 24 May 2020.
All schools, nurseries, Community College and UWI Open Campus will remain closed until 01 June 2020.
A ban is in place on all gatherings in public places of over 25 people, including schools, places of worship, places of entertainment or refreshment, funerals, sporting events and other social gatherings. Movement of people between islands is discouraged.
From 10 May 2020, church and funeral services will be limited to 10 people.
More information on local measures in place is available on the TCI Government website.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
